imagine we have a branch as master,
the commits on this branch can be different on local and remote server
(like when we cole the project, after that some one push some new commit on master)

so git need a new pointer to define the current branch on remote server!
like "origin/master"  (origin means original).
the "ORIGIN/MASTER" is remote tracking branch, and tell us where is
master branch in origin!

Note: similarly we have origin/HEAD
      that represent the HEAD pointer on server.


REMOTE SEVER:
                  MASTER
                    |
                    v
    +------+    +------+
    | C1   |<---| C2   |
    +------+    +------+



LOCAL SERVER:

      MASTER
        |
        v               Note: the local is not updated
    +------+                  he don't see the c2 commit on server yet.
    | C1   |
    +------+
        ^
        |
  origin/master


FETCH
we can download the c2 commit by "fetch" command
now the git knows that master on server point to another commit,
so he will move the origin/master pointer
but our master branch remained on c1
"SO THE WORKING DIRECTORY WILL NOT UPDATE BY FETCH"

      MASTER
        |
        v
    +------+    +------+
    | C1   |<---| C2   |
    +------+    +------+
                    ^
                    |
              origin/master

Note: if we want to our working directory get update,
      we need to move "MASTER" branch too.
      we need a merge for this, now we have not any divergence
      so it will a ff merge (some times it's a 3 way and has some conflicts):

      "git merge origin/master"         //will move master pointer to c2

